Jamie Reilly, Ph.D.

July 19, 2020

This session will cover Chapter 8 of the Field et al.text. We will focus on binary logistic regression (not polychotomous or multinomial)

Introduction

We will be using a merged psycholinguistic database values for many psycholinguistic variables across many English words. We will examine the capacity to discriminate verb from noun given a set of variables (length, semantic density) Filter rows by POS (brys_pos) - only nouns or verbs

big <- read.csv("Reilly_LexDbases_Merged_v1.csv", header=T) %>% clean_names %>% data.frame()
iso <- big %>% filter(brys_pos == "Verb" | brys_pos == "Noun") #isolate nouns and verbs
iso$brys_pos <- as.factor(iso$brys_pos)
iso$elp_naming_rt <- as.numeric(iso$elp_naming_rt)
iso$elp_sem_neighbors <- as.numeric(iso$elp_sem_neighbors)
iso$elp_lex_dec_rt <- as.numeric(iso$elp_lex_dec_rt)

Isolate Variables

Lets focus on six predictors in no particular order of importance. We will create a smaller dataframe just with these predictors along with word and grammatical class, including:
1. Total phonemes (kup_nphon)
2. Semantic diversity (elp_sem_diversity)
3. Lexical decision RT (elp_lex_dec_rt)
4. Concreteness (brys_concreteness)
5. Hand-Arm Salience (lnc_handarm)
6. Age-of-Acquisition (kup_aoa)

smaller <- iso %>% dplyr::select(1, 26, 14, 21, 22, 24, 34, 16) %>% data.frame()
colnames(smaller)
## [1] "word"              "brys_pos"          "kup_nphon"        
## [4] "elp_sem_diversity" "elp_lex_dec_rt"    "brys_concreteness"
## [7] "lnc_handarm"       "kup_aoa"

Well tackle PCA/factor reduction in a later session.

sample bias

You want roughly equal probabilities of events (nouns) and non-events (verbs). The log odds represent the probability of an event (observe noun) over the probability of a non-event (observe verb). It turns out with very large samples this isnt too problematic

table(smaller$brys_pos) # lots more nouns than verbs
## 
##  Noun  Verb 
## 14852  5379


Construct models

base model (mod0)

Intercept only model for examining deviance (lower is better)

Full model (mod1)

Forced entry all predictors. Grammatical class as a function of 6 variables all in one block. glm is generalized linear model

mod1 <- glm(brys_pos ~ kup_nphon + elp_sem_diversity + elp_lex_dec_rt + brys_concreteness + kup_aoa + lnc_handarm, data=smaller, family = binomial())
summary(mod1)

#Fit Is the full model (mod1) better than the base model (mod0)? goal of logistic regression is to develop a model that minimizes deviance residuals. Models with a McFadden pseudo R2 0.40 represents a very good fit.

list(mod1 = pscl::pR2(mod1)["McFadden"])
## fitting null model for pseudo-r2
## $mod1
##  McFadden 
## 0.2480425


Prediction

validation & test sets

Lets go back in time and develop equal-n training and validation sets. We will build a model fitted to the training data and validate its predictions on the test set. We will us the datapartition function to split the original dataframe into training and validation sets

set.seed(123)
trainIndex <- createDataPartition(smaller$brys_pos, p=0.7, list=FALSE, times=1)  #sample 70% of each factor
train <- smaller[trainIndex,] %>% data.frame
str(train)

build models

Lets build models for the training set

prediction in test set

Compute accuracy of the classification of noun or verb on the testing set

pred <- predict(valid.set, test, type="response", na.action = na.pass)

prediction error

computes prediction error of the model in the test set

misClassError(test$brys_pos, pred)  #computes prediction error as %
## [1] 0.4743


Diagnostics

multicollinearity

Variance inflation factor (VIF) should be below 4

vif(valid.set)  # not bad at all
